<title>USA: Chase, Salomon to help Colombia sell mine.</title>
<headline>Chase, Salomon to help Colombia sell mine.</headline>
<dateline>NEW YORK 1997-04-16</dateline>
<text>
<p>Chase Manhattan's Chase Securities unit said on Wednesday that it and Salomon Brothers Inc will advise the Colombian government on the privatization of its interest in the Cerrejon Zona Norte coal mine.</p>
<p>Chase said Cerrejon is one of the world's largest coal mines, with current production capacity of 15 million tons per year. Its assets include the coal mine, a railway from the mine to a port on the Guajira Peninsula, and the port facility itself.</p>
<p>Cerrejon is jointly owned by the government's Carbones de Colombia SA company and by International Resources Corp, a subsidiary of Exxon Corp.</p>
<p>Chase Securities' Global Mining &amp; Metals Group will work with Salomon in a consortium to advise Colombia on the sale, which Chase described as &quot;a significant step in Colombia's continuing privatization program.&quot;</p>
